Modern Java, not nineteen ninety-eight Java.

This track targets Java twenty-one, the current long term support release. A lot of older tutorials still teach the nineteen ninety-eight dialect of the language. We are going to write modern Java the whole way through.

There are five features you will use constantly that simply did not exist in old Java. The first is var, local variable type inference: you write var, then a name, then a value, and the compiler figures out the type for you. The second is text blocks, multi-line string literals written with three double quotes. The third is records, which give you a one-line immutable data class; you will meet those in module two. The fourth is pattern matching for switch, where switch becomes an expression that can pull a value apart. And the fifth is virtual threads, which let you run millions of cheap threads on one java virtual machine; those show up in module six.

Here is a simple tell. If you find an answer online that defines a whole class just to hold three fields, with a getter and a setter for each one, that is old Java. The problem is exactly the same, but modern Java solves it in a single line with a record.
